<br>
<br>
Talastius sat in dim morning twilight, looking out over the expanse of the Overthere, which had long since been his post, as it had been his father's. The fingers of daylight were creeping over the land, and aided by his infravision he could see them out there, all the things he had so easily hunted for as much sport and pleasure, as any sense of duty. He was confused, and hurt, and angry, and he couldn't grasp or understand why. It wasn't like him, it wasn't who he was. <br>
<br>
Angling his eyes up at the sky he saw the gathering clouds in the distance and found him self speaking aloud to no one, &quot;There is a storm coming.&quot; <br>
<br>
Pixxii was gone, but the confusion and chaos, the feelings he could not fully explain lingered. Only one other had ever made him feel in such a way, but that was another he had lost; and even then there had never been acknowledgement of anything on either parties part. But Pixxii, she had adored him and if such a thing exists, loved him openly and freely. Despite the prejudice and hatred drilled into him from his birth, the conditioning of his education as a knight of hatred, even his own malicious plans, he could not help but admit she had gotten to him, made him feel this way. <br>
<br>
He had come here, to his post, to hunt in peace and contemplate his future. She was gone, running to the safety of the dream realm, fearful of the coming darkness that would consume Talastius, knowing that it could not be stopped. He awoke that morning, and found himself alone. The one that had charmed him slipped forever away, and so he came here. Here he could hunt, here he could think, here he could be who he was. <br>
<br>
He wondered out, away from the safety of the oupost into the wilds. Little here was a threat to him anymore, the hunting being more sport than anything. It was in its own sense relaxing, a pleasant escape from the usual chaos of life. Soon he knew that he would have nothing left to learn here, his time serving in the outpost gone. But for now, he had his guilty pleasures terrorizing the local fauna.<br>
<br>
Lost in thought, Talastius never heard the stomping of the rhino. Out of nowhere it charged, slamming into the knight's back and tossing him to the side. Wincing in pain, Talastius rolled out of the way of the charging rhino and sprung to his feet, grabbing the mace hanging ready at his side. It was at that moment he first realized something was wrong.<br>
<br>
Pain shot through his arm, the Mace of the Shadowed Soul falling useless to the ground. Dodging another charge he cradled his arm a second and fumbled for another weapon. He was less skilled with the spear, but it would have to do. Deftly he planted the tip in the rhino's thick leathery side and smiled at his prey. Raising a hand he called on the dark magics to fill the beast with terror, but it would be Talastius that would panic. The energies would not form, the spell not take shape. Quickly he fumbled with the incantation of another, hoping to at least call darkness down on the beast. But the spell would not come, the magic gifts of his god had been revoked.<br>
<br>
The rhino thrashed, throwing Talastius to the ground, getting up again as quickly as he could he jerked his helmet off, that amongst the other bits of armor made for his order beginning to sting and burn the flesh underneath. As he stood there, contemplating his next move the rhino charged, its horn piercing through the armor as if it attacked a sheet of parchment. Talastius screamed in pain and threw out a fist, instincts driving him to deliver his harm touch. That it did not land held little surprise. Stumbling, Talastius grabbed his weapons and did the only thing the injured Tier Dal could do, he ran.<br>
<br>
In the Outpost General DeVeers and the others gathered around Talastius as he lie, bleeding and weak in one of the decrepid buildings. Some protested that Talastius had served well amongst them, balancing between his duties to his house, and his duties to his post. They said he should recieve attention, but the general would have none of it, instead ordering a captured Sarnak brought and chained, so the knight could tap its life force at his leisure. One by one they all left, save the general. When the two were alone he leaned over into the knight's face and whispered,<br>
&quot;I know everything.&quot;<br>
Spitting in Talastius's face, he straightened himself and went to leave the room, looking first at the paniced Sarnak and then sneering at the helpless knight on the ground.<br>
&quot;Drain it Talastius, if you can.&quot;<br>
<br>
Shortly there after Talastius slipped into a tortured dream, the pain and blood loss draining his strength.<br>
<br>
He was alone, on a desolate grey plain while harsh winds whipped about him. Figures moved in and out of the edge of his vision, never coming into view. He could hear voices, but not understand the things they said. Hands groped at him, though from where he coul not tell. As he spun in confusion and fear he saw him, a blurr at first in the distance, seated on a strange dark throne. As Talastius focused, the throne moved closer, the figure becoming more and more defined in shape and form.<br>
<br>
Talastius dropped to a knee and bowed his head in humility. &quot;My liege,&quot; he said.<br>
<br>
Naught stood from the throne, his motion strange and fluid. He looked down at the Tier Dal before him and smiled. The expression was both comforting and unsettling in its nature. Naught spoke:<br>
<br>
&quot;Funny, dat whut knights say, and yoo no knight Tal.&quot;<br>
<br>
Talastius rose slowly, looking up at the ogre. &quot;Yes, I am punished for my sins against my blood.&quot;<br>
<br>
Without moving his lips the ogre let loose a bellowing laugh that rattled the landscape and sent skeletal birds flying into a sky that was turning red and boiling like heated blood. Turning his gaze on Talastius he spoke without speaking.<br>
<br>
&quot;No Tal, yoo not bein' punished. Yoo bein' tested. Yoo lost yooself, let yooself be tainted. Now the gods want to know what yoo gonna do.&quot;<br>
<br>
Talastius looked down at the blood running down his side, pooling at his feet. As he looked into the pool, a purple mist bubbled up out of it, hovering and flowing all about. &quot;I'm going to die.&quot;<br>
<br>
A tentacle, emerged from the mist and wrapped itself around Talastius's leg, moving up his body, binding him and keeping him immobile. The warlord spoke again.<br>
<br>
&quot;So dat it den? Yoo jus gonna die. Yoo are weak now. She must have done a number on yoo bad. So is that what yoo want Tal, yoo wanna die? Or maybe yoo wanna go back, be wit her.&quot;<br>
<br>
Talastius leveled his gaze at the ogre and snarled at him, &quot;What I want is to be what I am. She dug things up, made me feel in ways I was not meant. I will not lie and tell you that I don't care for her, that she didn't touch me. But along that path is not my place, not my world. She is happy now, and better off where she is. My life would have destroyed all that she is. I don't want to be with her ogre, because it would destroy her and leave us both worse for wear. She is gone, nothing now but a memory of a few moments of feeling and a dream of a part of me that was never meant to be.&quot;<br>
<br>
The ogre smiled, and spoke again, the tentacle tightening with every word.<br>
<br>
&quot;So what yoo want then Tal? To be what yoo are? And what is dat?&quot;<br>
<br>
Talastius gasped for breath, the constriction making every word torture, &quot;A knight of shadows. A protector of the Tier Dal and a emissary of the Nightmare. I am hatred and anger, pain and torment. I want to serve again, to have purpose. To bring pride to my culture and to those I call brethren. I want to return to the Nightmare.&quot;<br>
<br>
The tentacle melted and faded away, dropping Talastius to the ground. He lay there, panting heavily as the ogre spoke.<br>
<br>
&quot;Then yoos gonna hafta get up an go Tal. Yoos got a long road and not much time. Yoos passed this test, but others are gonna come. And yoo made a sin against yoo blood Tal, yoo will be punished, yoo may even be killed. But if that what yoo want, yoo gonna hafta do it. Yoo gonna hafta go willingly and take what they throw an yoo gonna hafta thank dem for it. They gonna break yoo in ebery way. Death would be more merciful. Fleeing to your lover easier. So yoo gonna do it? Yoo gonna go back or yoo gonna run? Last chance.&quot;<br>
<br>
Talastius struggled to his feet. &quot;I... I'm going to return to the Nightmare, accept my penance, become myself again.&quot;<br>
<br>
The sky began raining in huge droplets, screaming as the blobs crashed into the ground. The ogre began to fade away. Talastius reached out to him.<br>
<br>
&quot;Naught....&quot;<br>
<br>
The voice spoke quietly from the ether around Talastius, &quot;No Tal, yoo on yoo own dis time. I don't know yoo. Maybe I know what yoo become, if yoo strong enough.&quot;<br>
<br>
And with that Talastius awoke from his fevered dream and sat up. Carefully he bandaged his side as best he could. He was already to weak to concentrate though, and the attempt made little difference overall. Staggering and weak, he got to his feet and gathered his things for his journey. <br>
<br>
As he moved slowly and painfully toward the doorway, his gaze settled on the Sarnak, still bound and huddled in a corner, awaiting its fate. Sneering, Talastius moved slowly toward it, stooping to pick a broken blade up off the ground. Smiling darkly he came up on the bound victim. Softly he said to it, &quot;Maybe I can't drain our essence, but that doesn't mean I'm harmless, by any means.&quot; The next morning Talastius was gone, and the guards found only the slaughtered body of the Sarnak, and some words written on the wall in its blood: You Know Nothing.<br>
<br>
The guards found him in the woods. His wounds infected and festering, the insects plaguing him. He was too incoherenat and near death to speak, and they doubted he knew where he was. Unsure what to do, they decided it was best to bring him back, present him to the Mistress and let her decide.<br>
<br>
For three days he lay, strapped to a slab in the bowels of Prime Nightmare's keep, screaming in torment as the maggots and bloodworms feasted on his wounds. Young healers of the house were called on to attend to him, to keep him hovering the line between tortured life, and merciful death. At the peaks of his torment, Brynvin would come to observe him, laughing sadistically at his suffering.<br>
<br>
&quot;Look at you...,&quot; she snarled, leaning inches over his face to be sure he could see the unbridled hatred in her eyes, &quot;Your hatred is as pale as your hair, your blood barely fit for the worms feeding on it... You have betrayed the very core of what you are, and what we stand for. You have grieved the only beings who ever cared about your pathetic existance... endured your madness... fought by your side... But they were not enough, were they? And still, when you have nothing left, not even a corpse to steal this time, you return to them. Tell me how it feels.&quot;<br>
<br>
As he writhed and bellowed in anguish, not answering her question, Brynvin took her leave, stopping to call back to him before leaving the chamber, &quot;But have no doubts, you who are so unworthy of redemption, we will take care of you. One way, or another.&quot;<br>
<br>
Three days he screamed before an audience was granted. He was cleaned and clothed and forced to march, weak and stumbling to the Mistress's chambers, where she would determine his fate.<br>
<br>
There collapsing to his knees, the fallen knight Talastius sat humbly before the grinning Mistress of Prime Nightmare, Lady Cielo Infierno. At her sides, the clerics Vyany and Brynvin sneered mockingly at Talastius. Unable to fully concentrate, the knight was aware of others in the room, most likely Fajon and Grogo. <br>
<br>
Finally, after much silence, Talastius spoke, bubbles of blood erupting from his lips, &quot;Forgive me.&quot; <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://mywebpages.comcast.net/JCOLE1/pnimages/Tal.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
