<br>
In truth, it was to be expected. Talastius was a guest of the house only in the sense that the Nightmare was never one to take prisoners. He sought redemption, and they sought to give it to him, but in the meantime he had to pay. All of his comforts were gone, and it would likely be a long time before he could again enjoy such things.<br>
<br>
Eventually exhaustion began to set in and sleep gripped the knight. <br>
<br>
Talastius found himself alone in a room of towering black walls that disappeared into the nighttime sky. The floor was covored in a few inches of perfectly still water, that aided by a soft light from some unknown source, offered an almost perfect reflection.<br>
<br>
As Talastius tried to get his bearings, he became aware of two entities behind him. Turning suddenly he gasped as he beheld them, the gods he served, towering silently over him. Dropping to his knees he bowed his head in humility. Slowly Innoruuk and Terris began to circle him, like sharks prepared to tear into some poor wayward water foul. Then the words came, slamming into his mind and threatening to drive him mad. The voice that carried them was so unnatural Talastius could not be certain which god spoke, or if it was somehow both of them. Clutching the sides of his head as the pain gripped him, Talastius took in the words of his gods.<br>
<br>
&quot;You have angered us wayward knight. You sought to corrupt, and failed and yourself became corrupted. You sinned against your bloodline and your flesh by bedding with the enemy of your people. Where we sought to give you everything, you sought to disgrace yourself. And for what? The affections of a Fier Dal that ran from you, wise enough to know that staying would bring only pain and torment? You threw out everything in a foolish game of emotion and gained nothing. And worse, you felt something. You weakened, lost your malicious way. And now you return, wishing to once again find yourself. Do you want it Talastius, do you want to return to what you were meant to be? Do you want all those things you dreamed? Are you willing to pay the price?'<br>
<br>
Talastius called out weakly, barely able to form words, &quot;I want to serve again. I want to be your knight.&quot;<br>
<br>
The voice of the gods boomed back at him, &quot;We are unhappy Talastius, but we are going to let you have your little redemption. But you will pay for your transgressions. What your brethren now prepare, is but one tiny piece of your punishment. Behold yourself Talastius, behold the price of sinning against your flesh.&quot;<br>
<br>
With trepidation Talastius looked down into the refective waters, focusing on his image there. What he saw sent the dark elf screaming in terror.<br>
<br>
The guards assigned to stand duty outside the knight's chambers burst in quickly, weapons drawn. The first to see Talastius froze in terror a few moment's before running from the room, bellowing for a cleric. The second watched the screaming knight clawing at the bubbling blisters and boils on his face and vomited. <br>
<br>
By morning Talastius had been treated as well as he could be before the coming ritual. But the efforts of the clerics proved to little avail. His face was a conglomerate of flayed flesh and festering wounds. Those that had healed, left horrible disfiguring scars. Ashamed to show his face, Talastius held his head low, his hair drapping in front fo his features as he was led from his room and to the place of trials.<br>
