  with the world that I once cherished<br>
  did it bring me to this darkened place<br>
  to contemplate my perfect future?<br>
  I will not stand nor utter words against this tide of hate<br>
  losing sight of what and who I was again&quot;<br>
<br>
  ~ &quot;Epicentre&quot; VNV Nation<br>
<br>
  Talastius knelt in his chambers before the small alter before him. The ritual of purification was over, and he was for all intents and purposes redeemed in the eyes of his people.<br>
  He knew the truth of course, redemption and forgiveness are by no means related, and some would never forget his crimes. With the physical trials complete, it was time to pray and meditate, and with the help of some potent teas, slip into the world of nightmares. There he would stand his final judgement before his gods, and only then would he truly be a knight again. He sat in silence for many hours, concentrating and freeing his mind. He sipped slowly from the ornate cup that held the brew. Finally the incense and tea took over and Talastius slumped and fell sideways, the cup slipping from his grip and crashing to the stone floor. <br>
<br>
  Outside the guards heard the breaking of glass, and the younger less experienced guard started for the door. His veteran companion grabbed his shoulder and pulled him back from the door.<br>
<br>
  &quot;No one goes in until he comes out. That is the way.&quot;<br>
<br>
  The younger guard nodded, accepting his mentors words and returned to his post.<br>
<br>
   <br>
&quot;why don't you deliver us from pain and evil <br>
  we stand in a quiver of our god and we will <br>
  follow his will as long as he will feed us <br>
  but we're not sure if he does really need us&quot; <br>
<br>
  ~ &quot;Deliverance&quot; Wumpscut<br>
<br>
<br>
  Talastius lay on a stone slab in an expanse of grey desolation. The light in the sky came from no sun or moon but from a ring of fire encircling the horizon, fading to the blackest nothingness as it climbed ever higher. His arms and legs were bound with writhing snakes that threatened to strike should he struggle too much. Venom like a thick black liquor dripped from their fangs. Their cold reptilian eyes spoke to Talastius all he needed to know:  this was his final chance. He could turn back now, forsake it all and surrender to death, or he could continue, and pray that his gods found him to once again be worthy.<br>
<br>
  Talastius stared coldly into the nothingness above him and spoke calmly, &quot;As I passed the test of my kin, so I shall pass this.&quot;<br>
<br>
  A voice thundered back at him, its volume and force threatening to implode his skull.<br>
<br>
  &quot;There are four you serve fallen knight. Name them and be redeemed, fail and the snakes shall strike. Are you prepared?&quot;<br>
<br>
  Talastius, grim and determined, called back to the voice that he was and the test began.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Who,&quot; thundered the wasteland around him, &quot;is your father, the one that made you?&quot;<br>
<br>
  Talastius called back without thinking, it was a simple answer, one every Tier'Dal knew  from birth, &quot;Innoruuk, God of Hatred.&quot;<br>
<br>
  The snake around his left arm loosened and dropped to the ground. As it writhed there, it grew and expanded, its shape changing until at last, the Hate God himself loomed above Talastius. Glaring down at his fallen knight, Innoruuk sneered and stepped back from the slab.<br>
<br>
  Again the voice called out.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Who is your queen, from whence all your desires are born.&quot;<br>
<br>
  Again Talastius found the answer easily, desires are but the product of dreams, and his dreams were the providence of Terris Thule. Upon answering the snake around his right arm loosened and dropped to the floor, growing as did the other until Terris towered above him. Silently she too stepped back from the slab.<br>
<br>
  The voice called out again, this time a tone of smugness could be detected.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Very good fallen knight. You have guessed with ease the two you knew you served, but what of those that bind your legs, what masters are those that you never knew you had? Tell me Talastius, who is your prophet, the one that inspires you?&quot;<br>
  His heart sunk and his throat seized. His inspiration? His prophet? He had never contemplated the thought, never considered the hand of another god in his life. And inspiration? Few would ever call him inspired, instead swinging more to deeming him...<br>
  That was it! It made sense, in a dark and terribly ironic way. They would call me mad he thought.<br>
<br>
  With the smugness of pride he shouted back, &quot;Vazaelle, the Mad God.&quot; <br>
<br>
  He felt the snake binding his left leg loosen and fall away, and in moments Vazaelle stood next to him, smiling in joy as tears of blood flowed from sorrowful eyes. She danced and whirled around the slab, in step with some rhythmless cacophony that he could not hear.<br>
<br>
  This time the voice thundered louder and harsher, obviously agitated.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Very well knight, now your final test. Who is your lover, Talastius? Who is the one that gives you pleasure?&quot;<br>
<br>
  Inside his own mind the knight growled in contempt. The voice wanted him to fail, and herein it saved its final, harshest question for last. Pleasure and love, the two very notions that had landed Talastius in this mess in the first place. It was a trap, he was certain, there could be no answer, no way to speak without incurring a fatal wrath.<br>
  Finally, resolved to his fate he yelled defiantly into the nothingness above.<br>
<br>
  &quot;What I would love, is to bring upon you a millennia of suffering, to make you watch your children bleed and whither into nothingness before I made you eat your own tongue!&quot;<br>
<br>
  For an eternity of moments there was silence, even Vazaelle stopped in her dance to glance at the knight, now waiting to die. Finally the three gods nodded in unspoken unison and the final snake loosened its grip and fell to the floor growing as the others had.<br>
<br>
  Talastius did not understand. He had not answered, had failed in the test. And then he saw the goddess before him and understood.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Saryn...&quot;<br>
<br>
  The goddess of pain came to him on that slab and before those assembled loved him with hooks and knives, teaching him to moan in the ecstasy of pain and scream in the torment of pleasure. She taught him so many things, and when she was done with him, she whispered in his ear, certain he was just conscious enough to hear her words.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Your flesh is mine and mine alone to play with.&quot;<br>
<br>
  <br>
&quot;In every dance no steps are placed, and on every path mistakes are made, and if every path leads but to the grave, let us dance upon our way.&quot;<br>
  ~ &quot;Scars Flown Proud&quot; Faith and the Muse<br>
<br>
<br>
  The guards outside Talastius' chamber snapped to attention as the door creaked open slowly. Talastius stumbled out and fell weakly to his knees, his palms on the ground. With great effort he spoke.<br>
<br>
  &quot;It is done.&quot;<br>
<br>
  The younger guard reached out to place a comforting hand on Talastius' shoulder and help him to his feet. As the guards palm touched his exposed shoulder, searing pain ripped through Talastius' body. The words of Saryn rang in his ears. Rising to his feet he snarled, pools of hatred filling his eyes. Lunging out he grabbed the guard by the throat, the contact almost too much to bear.<br>
<br>
  &quot;No one,&quot; Talastius snarled, &quot;is to ever touch me again.&quot; <br>
<br>
  Suddenly, instinctively the energies flowed through him and out his palm. The guard's eyes widened for a second as the harm touch struck him, and then Talastius dropped the limp corpse to the ground. Turning to the other guard, a demonic grin flashed across the knight's tattered face.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Take that to the clerics. See if they can revive him. If so, bring me my armor and weapons, I am out of practice, and as long as he can scream, he will make a fine practice dummy.&quot;<br>
<br>
  As he stepped toward his door, realization struck him and Talastius turned to give one ore order to the guard struggling with the still warm corpse.<br>
<br>
  &quot;And send some silver smiths and artisans to my chamber, I want a mask made.&quot;<br>
<br>
  The guard watched as Talastius walked, with more strength and confidence back into the all consuming darkness of his chamber. Carefully he worked his arms under the young recruit he was meant to train and drug the body down the hall toward the infirmary, stopping only to pass word to another hall guard.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Tell Lady Infierno, the knight is back.&quot;<br>
